<div class="dablink">This article is about Plato's Forms.  For other uses of "form" and "forms", see <a href="/wiki/Form_(disambiguation)" title="Form (disambiguation)" class="mw-redirect">Form (disambiguation)</a>.  For other uses of the term "eidos", see <a href="/wiki/Eidos_(disambiguation)" title="Eidos (disambiguation)">Eidos (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p><a href="/wiki/Plato" title="Plato">Plato</a>'s <b>Theory of Forms</b><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> asserts that <b>Forms</b> (or <b><a href="/wiki/Idea" title="Idea">Ideas</a></b>), and not the material world of change <a href="/wiki/Plato%27s_allegory_of_the_cave" title="Plato's allegory of the cave" class="mw-redirect">known to us through sensation</a>, possess the highest and most fundamental kind of reality. The Forms are the only true objects of study that can provide us with genuine knowledge. <sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Plato spoke of forms (sometimes capitalized in translations: <b>The Forms</b>)<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> in formulating <a href="/wiki/Platonic_realism" title="Platonic realism">his solution</a> to the <a href="/wiki/Problem_of_universals" title="Problem of universals">problem of universals</a>.</p>
